## 3. Database Models (models.py)

All 7 models use **String(10) primary keys** (e.g., "T001", "C001", "G031").

| Model | Table | PK | Key Fields |
|---|---|---|---|
| `Teacher` | teachers | `id` (T001…) | name, department, max_consecutive (default 3) |
| `Course` | courses | `id` (C001…) | code, name, sessions_required, is_elective |
| `Room` | rooms | `id` (R001…) | name, faculty (building), capacity, room_type (Lecture/Lab) |
| `StudentGroup` | student_groups | `id` (G001…) | name, total_students |
| `TimeSlot` | time_slots | `id` (TS001…) | day (Mon–Fri), start_time, end_time |
| `CourseOffering` | course_offerings | `id` (O001…) | course_id (FK), teacher_id (FK), group_id (FK) |
| `Schedule` | schedules | `id` (auto int) | offering_id (FK), room_id (FK), timeslot_id (FK) |

**CourseOffering** is the central unit the algorithm schedules — it links one Course × Teacher × StudentGroup.
**Schedule** is the output table — each row assigns an offering to a room and time slot.

